00:27:47.580 --> 00:27:51.580
And in the end, I said to the firm, I said, I'm sorry, they're coming back here now,

00:27:51.580 --> 00:27:53.580
I said too many times.

00:27:53.580 --> 00:27:56.580
Because there was myself and another girl doing it.

00:27:56.580 --> 00:28:03.580
And I said, they're getting paid more than what we are for turning out about for the rubbish.

00:28:03.580 --> 00:28:10.580
So in the end, he tried to stop the piecework until they got to a better quality

00:28:10.580 --> 00:28:12.580
of making the belt.

00:28:12.580 --> 00:28:15.580
And then they brought it back in then.

00:28:15.580 --> 00:28:20.580
But as soon as they knew they could earn more money, they just seemed to...

00:28:20.580 --> 00:28:23.580
So who was checking the...did you have quality control sort of thing?

00:28:23.580 --> 00:28:24.580
Was that the foreman's job?

00:28:24.580 --> 00:28:26.580
Yeah, the foreman did that.

00:28:26.580 --> 00:28:29.580
And you see him walking around with half a dozen belts on one hand

00:28:29.580 --> 00:28:31.580
and half a dozen belts on the other.

00:28:31.580 --> 00:28:34.580
And you're thinking, oh, I wish that one there with the least on his arm

00:28:34.580 --> 00:28:37.580
was the ones that didn't need repaired.

00:28:37.580 --> 00:28:43.580
Because when you had to repair a belt, you had to unpick it.

00:28:43.580 --> 00:28:45.580
And then you had to redo it.

00:28:45.580 --> 00:28:50.580
And the more times you unpick something, the flimsier it gets.

00:28:50.580 --> 00:28:55.580
So in the end, he did try and stop it.

00:28:55.580 --> 00:28:59.580
And he said, right, it's going to be stopped here, it's going to be stopped now.

00:28:59.580 --> 00:29:04.580
If I don't quality control these belts and pass them, you don't get paid for them.

00:29:04.580 --> 00:29:09.580
So then they all started putting their socks up then and doing it as they should be.

00:29:09.580 --> 00:29:12.580
And did you have to clock in and out?

00:29:12.580 --> 00:29:13.580
Yes.

00:29:13.580 --> 00:29:15.580
How did you work then?

00:29:15.580 --> 00:29:18.580
Eight o'clock. We started eight o'clock.

00:29:18.580 --> 00:29:21.580
And I think it was five. Eight till five.

00:29:21.580 --> 00:29:22.580
Long day.

00:29:22.580 --> 00:29:27.580
Yeah, you had a break in the morning and a break in the afternoon.

00:29:28.580 --> 00:29:32.580
And then you had, I think it was an hour, I think we had for dinner.

00:29:32.580 --> 00:29:36.580
It must have been an hour we had for dinner because we used to get up to rares.

00:29:36.580 --> 00:29:39.580
Sometimes we'd go to the black and white and have a bit of dinner.

00:29:39.580 --> 00:29:41.580
What was the black and white?

00:29:41.580 --> 00:29:44.580
The black and white is on the corner of North Clive Street.

00:29:44.580 --> 00:29:46.580
It's actually still there now.

00:29:46.580 --> 00:29:49.580
We used to do lovely dinners there.

00:29:49.580 --> 00:29:51.580
Is that a cafe or a pub?

00:29:51.580 --> 00:29:52.580
It was a cafe.

00:29:52.580 --> 00:29:56.580
Or if we went to the pub, we'd have to take the foreman with us.

00:29:56.580 --> 00:30:00.580
We weren't old enough at first, I wasn't old enough really to drink.

00:30:00.580 --> 00:30:02.580
But the foreman came with us.

00:30:02.580 --> 00:30:05.580
If you're going for the pub, I'm going to watch what you're drinking.

00:30:05.580 --> 00:30:08.580
And he made sure we only ever had one glass.

00:30:08.580 --> 00:30:16.580
And it was just like being with family, not workmates.

00:30:16.580 --> 00:30:20.580
But here you are, in an instance.

00:30:20.580 --> 00:30:24.580
My auntie was looking, not the auntie that took me for an interview, another auntie.

00:30:24.580 --> 00:30:26.580
She was having family problems.

00:30:26.580 --> 00:30:31.580
She'd moved back down here and she wanted a job.

00:30:31.580 --> 00:30:33.580
Of course, nothing going.

00:30:33.580 --> 00:30:36.580
So I mentioned to the foreman and he said, well, what can she do?

00:30:36.580 --> 00:30:39.580
I said, well, she'd lay her hand on anything.

00:30:39.580 --> 00:30:41.580
She'd try anything.

00:30:41.580 --> 00:30:47.580
He said, well, we're looking for somebody to coat the fibreglass belts.

00:30:47.580 --> 00:30:49.580
With the fibreglass.

00:30:49.580 --> 00:30:54.580
If you weaved a belt, it was really, really strong if you pulled it that way.

00:30:54.580 --> 00:30:58.580
But if you rubbed your finger on it, it would fray.

00:30:58.580 --> 00:31:00.580
That's how fragile it was.

00:31:00.580 --> 00:31:05.580
So with the fibreglass belts, they used to get dipped into a solution.

00:31:05.580 --> 00:31:10.580
And then put on a stretcher to stretch it back to the size that it was.

00:31:10.580 --> 00:31:15.580
He said, we're actually looking for somebody, he said, to help Lily to do,

00:31:15.580 --> 00:31:19.580
Lily was another lady that worked there, to help her do this job.

00:31:19.580 --> 00:31:21.580
Do you think she'd have a go at that?

00:31:21.580 --> 00:31:24.580
I said, well, you can only ask.

00:31:24.580 --> 00:31:27.580
Anyway, she did, she came and worked there and she did it.

00:31:27.580 --> 00:31:29.580
She did it for quite a while.

00:31:29.580 --> 00:31:34.580
And then her husband came back on the scene and she didn't know whether to go back with her husband

00:31:34.580 --> 00:31:36.580
or whether to stay where she was too.

00:31:36.580 --> 00:31:38.580
You're one very nice person, the husband.

00:31:38.580 --> 00:31:43.580
And I'm talking about my mother's sister, so she's a lot older than me.

00:31:43.580 --> 00:31:48.580
And the foreman said, well, look, you've got a job here.

00:31:48.580 --> 00:31:53.580
If you don't feel safe, I can get you a job in another mill.

00:31:53.580 --> 00:32:00.580
And I can even get people up in that mill to house you, to get you away.

00:32:03.580 --> 00:32:05.580
And she wouldn't do it.

00:32:05.580 --> 00:32:07.580
She wouldn't do it.

00:32:07.580 --> 00:32:11.580
She stayed with us for a little bit longer than her husband was making a nuisance,

00:32:11.580 --> 00:32:13.580
so she went back to her husband.

00:32:13.580 --> 00:32:16.580
And it didn't end up very nice.

00:32:16.580 --> 00:32:20.580
But she wished, he's gone now, the husband.

00:32:20.580 --> 00:32:27.580
She wished that she would have taken his offer of help then.

00:32:27.580 --> 00:32:30.580
But that's the sort of person he was.

00:32:30.580 --> 00:32:35.580
He wasn't like a foreman that you get today.

00:32:35.580 --> 00:32:38.580
He was like family.

00:32:38.580 --> 00:32:40.580
All of them was like family.

00:32:40.580 --> 00:32:44.580
Everybody got on with everybody else.

00:32:44.580 --> 00:32:47.580
I just had a new job there.

00:32:47.580 --> 00:32:54.580
So were the photos that you've shown me, so did all these girls work on your side?

00:32:54.580 --> 00:32:55.580
Yes.

00:32:55.580 --> 00:33:01.580
I haven't got any photographs of the other side doing the flastic belts.

00:33:01.580 --> 00:33:07.580
But I do bump into Pam very often.

00:33:07.580 --> 00:33:16.580
To be honest, I think there's only really two people now, which is Pam and I think it was Yvonne.

00:33:16.580 --> 00:33:21.580
They were the only two people, I think, that's left from the flastic side.

00:33:21.580 --> 00:33:24.580
I think the others have passed.

00:33:24.580 --> 00:33:27.580
Lily, I got on really well with Lily.

00:33:27.580 --> 00:33:34.580
She was doing the flastics and then she went to help my auntie with coating the fiberglass belts.

00:33:34.580 --> 00:33:39.580
Well, her daughter ended up having a job in the actual office.

00:33:39.580 --> 00:33:47.580
So if you knew a job was going, it would be given to people that was inside, knowing.

00:33:47.580 --> 00:33:52.580
We had lots of trips and things.

00:33:52.580 --> 00:33:58.580
I was going to say, so about your outings and Christmas parties or things like that.

00:33:58.580 --> 00:34:03.580
We always seemed to be going somewhere, always seemed to be doing something.

00:34:03.580 --> 00:34:10.580
Like on a Christmas time, you'd actually have a party on the actual shop floor.

00:34:11.580 --> 00:34:16.580
Another thing now, just thinking of it now, it would never happen now in this day and age.

00:34:16.580 --> 00:34:21.580
We had something wrong with the big fluorescent lights over the looms.

00:34:21.580 --> 00:34:30.580
The person that came to fix them was actually somebody that my husband knew from Penturg.

00:34:30.580 --> 00:34:34.580
We didn't know he was coming, so I'm on my loom now and I'm weaving away.

00:34:34.580 --> 00:34:37.580
You are literally bouncing, weaving.

00:34:37.580 --> 00:34:42.580
That's all I heard was this fella laughing his head off, I was going to swear then.

00:34:42.580 --> 00:34:44.580
He was laughing his head off.

00:34:44.580 --> 00:34:48.580
I said, I recognize that laugh, so I'm looking round like this now.

00:34:48.580 --> 00:34:50.580
He's up the ladder.

00:34:50.580 --> 00:34:53.580
He said, actually over a loom, somebody is working repairing the lights.

00:34:53.580 --> 00:34:57.580
So you wouldn't have that now today, it would all happen safely.

00:34:57.580 --> 00:35:01.580
I looked at him and I said, oh, I recognize that laugh.

00:35:01.580 --> 00:35:02.580
What are you doing here?

00:35:02.580 --> 00:35:04.580
He said, what the hell does it look as though I'm doing?

00:35:04.580 --> 00:35:05.580
I meant in the light.

00:35:05.580 --> 00:35:06.580
What are you doing?

00:35:06.580 --> 00:35:10.580
He said, oh my God, I've never seen anything so funny.

00:35:10.580 --> 00:35:12.580
He said, you're bouncing around like a blue arse.

00:35:12.580 --> 00:35:15.580
This is his exact words, a blue arse.

00:35:15.580 --> 00:35:18.580
I said, what's that you're weaving about?

00:35:18.580 --> 00:35:22.580
So he stood there, he got down off the ladder and he stood there and he watched me

00:35:22.580 --> 00:35:27.580
and the person that was next to me, seeing who was the fastest to weave it.

00:35:27.580 --> 00:35:31.580
I can't believe that, I can't believe that, he said.

00:35:31.580 --> 00:35:33.580
I've never seen anything so funny.

00:35:33.580 --> 00:35:35.580
I said, oh thank you very much.

00:35:35.580 --> 00:35:38.580
I said, this is my job and I enjoy it, so go do yours.

00:35:38.580 --> 00:35:41.580
But he did, he fixed the lights.

00:35:41.580 --> 00:35:45.580
Then when we actually went up to Penton to see my husband's parents,

00:35:45.580 --> 00:35:49.580
he lived a couple of doors away and he actually seen the car and he came down.

00:35:49.580 --> 00:35:54.580
He said, oh Keith, he said, which was my husband, Keith, have you ever seen a weaving?

00:35:54.580 --> 00:35:56.580
No, he said, I don't see a weaving.

00:35:56.580 --> 00:35:57.580
He said, her hands are bad enough.

00:35:57.580 --> 00:36:00.580
He said, it's like having something rubbing on your back.

00:36:00.580 --> 00:36:02.580
He said, we're full of calluses, he said.

00:36:02.580 --> 00:36:05.580
He said, you don't need a back scratcher.

00:36:05.580 --> 00:36:08.580
So he said, oh my god, I've never seen anything so funny.

00:36:08.580 --> 00:36:11.580
He said, they're bouncing all over the place, he said.

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:13.580
They're swinging on the top of the thing.

00:36:13.580 --> 00:36:15.580
He said, she must have messed up the spike part by.

00:36:15.580 --> 00:36:18.580
That was the exact words, I always remember it.

00:36:18.580 --> 00:36:21.580
It's a cheeky sewing soul.

00:36:21.580 --> 00:36:23.580
But we loved it.

00:36:23.580 --> 00:36:27.580
And we did used to have races to see who could finish a belt.

00:36:27.580 --> 00:36:29.580
Was it a dangerous word, do you think?

00:36:29.580 --> 00:36:31.580
Was there any sort of?

00:36:31.580 --> 00:36:34.580
It was only dangerous if the weights fell off and it would be on a finger.

00:36:34.580 --> 00:36:38.580
Because once the belt was put in, you had an arm,

00:36:38.580 --> 00:36:42.580
you pull this arm down and there would be three grooves, three or four grooves,

00:36:42.580 --> 00:36:48.580
and you would pick up weights, big weights,

00:36:48.580 --> 00:36:53.580
and put them on the end of this arm to stretch the belt.

00:36:53.580 --> 00:36:57.580
If it wasn't heavy enough, you'd take another round weight,

00:36:57.580 --> 00:37:00.580
stick it on the thing.

00:37:00.580 --> 00:37:02.580
Like the ones you sell on those old scales.

00:37:02.580 --> 00:37:06.580
Yeah, but there was a groove in it to hit on a thing.

00:37:06.580 --> 00:37:09.580
And very often, you'd put too many weights on, nothing,

00:37:09.580 --> 00:37:13.580
and when you go to take it off, you'd be over the machine.

00:37:13.580 --> 00:37:19.580
You could stab yourself with a needle, the wire could snap.

00:37:19.580 --> 00:37:25.580
You could fall and trip and break your neck on all the strings that were on the floor.

00:37:25.580 --> 00:37:29.580
Because the strings I've brought you here now, it's not strings, it's cotton.

00:37:29.580 --> 00:37:36.580
This one ball of cotton here, you could make belts out of that.

00:37:39.580 --> 00:37:42.580
But there were so many different thicknesses.

00:37:42.580 --> 00:37:47.580
And the way you do the thicknesses is you then twist it,

00:37:49.580 --> 00:37:52.580
and you'd have three strands.

00:37:52.580 --> 00:37:58.580
And in each of those strands, you've got to bear with me now because I've got glasses on now, I'm going blind.

00:37:58.580 --> 00:38:05.580
On each of these strands, you have three strands.

00:38:05.580 --> 00:38:07.580
See the three strands in each of the strands?

00:38:07.580 --> 00:38:10.580
Oh, God, yeah.

00:38:10.580 --> 00:38:12.580
That's three, six, nine.

00:38:12.580 --> 00:38:17.580
So that would be a ball of nine sixteenths.

00:38:18.580 --> 00:38:24.580
Then you'd have another one that would have four strands with different amounts in.

00:38:24.580 --> 00:38:26.580
And each one would be thicker and thicker.

00:38:26.580 --> 00:38:28.580
This was the thinnest one.

00:38:28.580 --> 00:38:35.580
But you could have 12 sixteenths, 18, they're all different sizes.

00:38:35.580 --> 00:38:42.580
And you make a belt with different size cotton.

00:38:42.580 --> 00:38:46.580
So they'd be different thicknesses, different widths.

00:38:46.580 --> 00:38:54.580
And would you do a certain amount of one size and then move on to another?

00:38:54.580 --> 00:38:57.580
You know what you'd have to do for that day sort of thing?

00:38:57.580 --> 00:39:06.580
The foreman would come over and say, right, I need, say, six three and a half inch cotton.

00:39:06.580 --> 00:39:08.580
So somebody would say, oh yeah, I'll do them.

00:39:08.580 --> 00:39:11.580
But then he'd say, right, okay, then you can do two, you can do two.

00:39:11.580 --> 00:39:13.580
And we'd split them up.

00:39:13.580 --> 00:39:15.580
So they're doing different ones.

00:39:15.580 --> 00:39:21.580
Because the thicker the stuff, the harder the belt was to do.

00:39:21.580 --> 00:39:26.580
This was harder on your fingers because you'd actually catch it.

00:39:26.580 --> 00:39:29.580
If you were weaving like this, you'd actually catch it.

00:39:29.580 --> 00:39:32.580
So the thinner it was, the more chance you'd have a cut.

00:39:32.580 --> 00:39:34.580
Yeah.

00:39:34.580 --> 00:39:39.580
The thicker the one that was, it was easier on your little fingers.

00:39:39.580 --> 00:39:46.580
But it was harder to beat because you had to keep the same width in between each of those.

00:39:46.580 --> 00:39:48.580
Your hands look fine now.

00:39:48.580 --> 00:39:50.580
They're lovely now, yeah.

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:53.580
Fairly liquid hands.

00:39:53.580 --> 00:39:56.580
But honestly, you couldn't, I couldn't weave with rings on.

00:39:56.580 --> 00:40:04.580
You'd have to take your rings off because you would literally have on each of your fingers there underneath the pants,

00:40:04.580 --> 00:40:08.580
you would actually have blisters.

00:40:08.580 --> 00:40:13.580
But with working so much, they would go hard.

00:40:13.580 --> 00:40:17.580
Like calluses, they were calluses on your hands.

00:40:17.580 --> 00:40:20.580
So we didn't, none of us had very nice hands.

00:40:20.580 --> 00:40:24.580
The only ones that had nice hands was the ones that were using them up on buckets.

00:40:24.580 --> 00:40:29.580
Because it was soft weaving.

00:40:29.580 --> 00:40:32.580
And they actually had a metal beater.

00:40:32.580 --> 00:40:34.580
They used a shuttle.

00:40:34.580 --> 00:40:38.580
They'd throw the shuttle through and catch it with this hand and they'd beat it like that.

00:40:38.580 --> 00:40:44.580
Whereas ours, we'd use our, same as them, they had their feet to open the shafts.

00:40:44.580 --> 00:40:51.580
We'd open the shafts with our feet, but we had a beater that you had to use two hands and pull your whole weight.

00:40:51.580 --> 00:40:55.580
Just like rowing, you know how a rower goes.

00:40:55.580 --> 00:41:03.580
You would literally be pulling it because the string would be around, or the cotton rather, would be around the beater.

00:41:03.580 --> 00:41:11.580
So each time you'd flick your beater, bang, flick, bang, flick, just to let the cotton come off.

00:41:11.580 --> 00:41:14.580
It was physical, wasn't it?

00:41:14.580 --> 00:41:18.580
Yeah, it was. You had enough exercise to last you a lifetime.

00:41:18.580 --> 00:41:28.580
And when that beater then became empty with the cotton, you'd just hold it in your hand by that and just go round and round and round.

00:41:29.580 --> 00:41:35.580
And when it was full then you'd start off again and do it again.

00:41:35.580 --> 00:41:42.580
But I've got to be fair, if they opened up another one, but everything's all electrical now, isn't it?

00:41:42.580 --> 00:41:46.580
They showed online last night all the electric looms.

00:41:46.580 --> 00:41:49.580
So you must stand there and watch it now, don't you, I suppose?

00:41:49.580 --> 00:42:03.580
Yeah, yeah. Because Anne, who is this lady here, she started there before me, but she didn't have any ideas on how to warp one of the wider belts.

00:42:03.580 --> 00:42:11.580
She used a power loom which made an inch wide belt, but it was really long.

00:42:11.580 --> 00:42:21.580
So it must have used about, I say, 12 wires, but they had big holes in the wires.

00:42:21.580 --> 00:42:31.580
And she'd just done them in a matter of seconds and then put them onto this loom and she'd just pressed the button while it wound the button, it was angled.

00:42:31.580 --> 00:42:38.580
She stood there on the handle and when that was finished then, she was supposed to have sewed them in, what we call sewed them in, finished it off.

00:42:38.580 --> 00:42:43.580
And she just used to hang them up and forget about them.

00:42:43.580 --> 00:42:50.580
And then when I was sat talking, I pulled one down, I'm talking to a nice sewing in and somebody else would go over and talk to it and they just sort of form them.

00:42:50.580 --> 00:42:55.580
Couldn't say, you're not doing any work. But we'd help one another.

00:42:55.580 --> 00:43:05.580
And there was one loom, I don't know why every loom looked the same, but there was one loom that everybody loved.

00:43:05.580 --> 00:43:08.580
I don't know what it was, they were all exactly the same.

00:43:08.580 --> 00:43:12.580
And we used to fight to try and get on this one loom.

00:43:12.580 --> 00:43:20.580
And if somebody hadn't finished the belt by the time you were due to go home and the belt was still in that loom,

00:43:20.580 --> 00:43:32.580
and a person came in earlier in the morning, they'd jump on that loom quick, finished the belt off, hanging up ready for the other woman to come in, and they'd put their belt in to do it.

00:43:32.580 --> 00:43:41.580
I don't know why, even myself, I was the same. That one loom always seemed to have a better quality belt on it.

00:43:41.580 --> 00:43:47.580
So you never had the same work plate, you didn't have your one loom and that's the one that you suck with?

00:43:47.580 --> 00:43:52.580
No, whatever was finished on our loom, and if it was empty, anybody.

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:56.580
So you'd be looking around to see who was nearest.

00:43:56.580 --> 00:44:01.580
If you got a couple months going, you'd really go mad trying to finish putting the wires in.

00:44:01.580 --> 00:44:06.580
And very often two of you would be there, oh go on then, you can have it.

00:44:06.580 --> 00:44:15.580
But I know one girl who used to warp two belts and hang it upside down with the wires on the bottom so they wouldn't get tangled.

00:44:15.580 --> 00:44:21.580
And she would literally wait until that loom was empty before she went and weaved.

00:44:21.580 --> 00:44:30.580
But it was identical to all the others. I can't, I've used all of looms and this one loom was different.

00:44:30.580 --> 00:44:47.580
The only thing that we had of our own, well I add on my own anyway, I always wanted to keep my own wires and my own rods, my own beater, my own needle and my own tape.

00:44:47.580 --> 00:44:50.580
And everybody then started to keep their own.

00:44:50.580 --> 00:45:01.580
And if you were on holidays, what you'd do, the foreman would give you greased ground paper and you'd put your wires in there and you'd wrap it in the ground paper.

00:45:01.580 --> 00:45:05.580
You'd put your name on it and you'd say right there, there for when you come back off your holidays.

00:45:05.580 --> 00:45:08.580
